        <h1>Measurement Logging Guide</h1>

        <div class="guide-step">
            <h2>Step 1: Set up your equipment.</h2>
            <p>* Prepare your Sky Quality Meter, Bortle Scale chart, or Light Pollution measurement app for measurements.</p>
            <div id="tools-img">
                <div>
                    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/SQM-l.jpg/800px-SQM-l.jpg"
                        alt="Sky Quality Meter">
                    <p>Sky Quality Meter</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <img src="https://darkskydiary.files.wordpress.com/2012/01/bortlescaleflowchart2.jpg"
                        alt="Bortle Scale Chart">
                    <p>Bortle Scale Chart</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <img src="https://scx2.b-cdn.net/gfx/news/hires/2013/igb-loss-of-the-night-app.jpg"
                        alt="Loss of the Night App Poster">
                    <p>Light Pollution measurement app</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-step">
            <h2>Step 2: Choose a location</h2>
            <p>* Find a location with minimal light pollution for accurate measurements.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-step">
            <h2>Step 3: Follow the guide to record accurate measurements.</h2>
            <p>* Follow the detailed guide for recording measurements using your chosen equipment.</p>
            <p>* For measurements in values of Naked Eye Limiting magnitude, convert the measurement to the corresponding
                Bortle Class before logging.</p>
            <img src="https://cdn.darkskyarkansas.org/blobarnaturalsa18ca2d3dc/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/cap-307.jpg"
                alt="Comprehensive Conversion Chart">
            <p>* Once you obtain the values, log in to AstroSentinel, search and click on your location on the map, and
                  input the values as prompted. That will add a marker at the location of your recorded measurements.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

